TY  - JOUR
AU  - Che, Yeon-Koo
AU  - Iossa, Elisabetta
AU  - Rey, Patrick
T1  - Prizes versus Contracts as Incentives for Innovation
PY  - 2021
Y1  - 2021/10/01
DO  - 10.1093/restud/rdaa092
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 88
IS  - 5
SP  - 2149
EP  - 2178
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - Procuring an innovation involves motivating a research effort to generate a new idea and then implementing that idea efficiently. If research efforts are unverifiable and implementation costs are private information, a trade-off arises between the two objectives. The optimal mechanism resolves the trade-off via two instruments: a cash prize and a follow-on contract. It primarily uses the latter, by favouring the innovator at the implementation stage when the value of the innovation is above a certain threshold and handicapping the innovator when the value of the innovation is below that threshold. A cash prize is employed as a supplementary incentive only when the value of innovation is sufficiently high. These features are consistent with current practices in the procurement of innovation and the management of unsolicited proposals.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdaa092
ER  - 



